[[File:Hucks Gibbs, 1st Baron Aldenham.jpg|thumb|Hucks Gibbs, 1st Baron Aldenham]] '''Henry Hucks Gibbs, 1st Baron Aldenham''' [[Master of Arts|MA]] [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] [[Geological Society|FGS]] [[Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] (31 August 1819 – 13 September 1907) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] banker, businessman and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician.
==Life== Aldenham the son of George Henry Gibbs,<ref name="times-1907-09-14">{{cite news |url=http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/987/860/138315448w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS101905710&dyn=13!nxt_10_0_CS101905710 |title=Obituary. Lord Aldenham |date=14 September 1907 |work=The Times |page=6, col C |accessdate=6 February 2011 |location=London }} {{subscription}}</ref> whose father Antony Gibbs was a brother of [[Vicary Gibbs|Sir Vicary Gibbs]], a [[Chief Justice of the Common Pleas]].<ref name="times-obit">{{cite news |url=http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/987/860/138315448w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS236135982&dyn=51!nxt_16_0_CS236135982 |title=Mr. Vicary Gibbs "The Complete Peerage" |date=14 January 1932 |work=The Times |page=14, col D |accessdate=6 February 2011 |location=London }} {{subscription}}</ref> He was a Senior Partner in the family firm of [[Antony Gibbs & Sons]], and was a Director of the [[Bank of England]] from 1853 to 1901, its [[Deputy Governor of the Bank of England|Deputy Governor]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/about/pdfs/deputygovernors.pdf |title=Deputy Governors of the Bank of England |publisher=[[Bank of England]] |accessdate=3 January 2014 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and finally its [[Governor of the Bank of England|Governor]] from 1875 to 1877.
He was elected as a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[City of London (UK Parliament constituency)|City of London]] at an unopposed<ref name="craig1885-1918" /> by-election in April 1891,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue= 26154 |date= 21 April 1891 |page=2176 }}</ref> and held the seat until the [[United Kingdom general election, 1892|general election in July 1892]],<ref>{{Rayment-hc|l|3|date=March 2012}}</ref> when his oldest son [[Alban Gibbs, 2nd Baron Aldenham|Alban]] was elected in his place.<ref name="craig1885-1918">{{cite book |last=Craig |first=F. W. S. |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig |title=British parliamentary election results 1885–1918 |origyear=1974 |edition= 2nd |year=1989 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-27-2 |page=11 }}</ref> He also held the office of [[High Sheriff of Hertfordshire]] in 1884.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue= 25326 |date= 7 March 1884 |page=1122 }}</ref> In 1896 he was raised to the peerage as '''Baron Aldenham''', of Aldenham in the County of Hertford.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue= 26706 |date= 4 February 1896 |page=645 }}</ref> A member of the [[Philological Society]], he was a major benefactor to the [[Oxford English Dictionary]].
==Family== Lord Aldenham married Louisa Anne, daughter of William Adams and the Hon. Mary Anne Cokayne, in 1845. Their fourth son the Hon. Herbert Cokayne Gibbs was created [[Baron Hunsdon of Hunsdon]] in 1923 while their fifth son the Venerable the Hon. Kenneth Francis Gibbs was [[Archdeacon of St Albans]]. Lady Aldenham died in 1897. Lord Aldenham survived her by ten years and died in September 1907, aged 88. He was succeeded in the barony by his eldest son [[Alban Gibbs, 2nd Baron Aldenham|Alban]].{{sfn|Welch|1912}}
Children of Lord and Lady Aldenham: *[[Alban Gibbs, 2nd Baron Aldenham]] 1846-1936 *Hon. Edith Caroline Gibbs 1848-1942 *Walter Antony Gibbs 1850-1858 *Hon. [[Vicary Gibbs (St Albans MP)|Vicary Gibbs]] 1853-1932 *[[Herbert Gibbs, 1st Baron Hunsdon]] 1854-1935 *Venerable Hon. Kenneth Francis Gibbs 1856-1935 *Hon. Henry Lloyd Gibbs 1861-1907
